  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_750",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Doppelganger Obfuscation - Exploring the Defensive and Offensive Aspects of Hardware Camouflaging",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Max Hoffmann",
        "email": "hoffmann@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Christof Paar",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Hardware obfuscation is widely used in practice to counteract reverse engineering.\nIn recent years, low-level obfuscation via camouflaged gates has been increasingly discussed in the scientific community and industry.\nIn contrast to classical high-level obfuscation, such gates result in recovery of an erroneous netlist.\nThis technology has so far been regarded as a purely defensive tool.\nWe show that low-level obfuscation is in fact a double-edged sword that can also enable stealthy malicious functionalities.\n\nIn this work, we present Doppelganger, the first generic design-level obfuscation technique that is based on low-level camouflaging.\nDoppelganger obstructs central control modules of digital designs, e.g., FSMs or bus controllers,\nresulting in two different design functionalities: an apparent one that is recovered during reverse engineering and the actual one that is executed during operation.\nNotably, both functionalities are under the designer's control.\n\nIn two case studies, we apply Doppelganger to a universal cryptographic coprocessor.\nFirst, we show the defensive capabilities by presenting the reverse engineer with a different mode of operation than the one that is actually executed.\nThen, for the first time, we demonstrate the considerable threat potential of low-level obfuscation.\nWe show how an invisible, remotely exploitable key-leakage Trojan can be injected into the same cryptographic coprocessor just through obfuscation.\nIn both applications of Doppelganger, the resulting design size is indistinguishable from that of an unobfuscated design, depending on the choice of encodings.",
    "keywords": [
      "Hardware Obfuscation",
      "Camouflaging",
      "Hardware Trojans"
    ],
    "category": "",
    "publication_info": "Published by the IACR in TCHES 2021",
    "last_updated": "2021-05-25",
